04333nam a22006615i 9780226552118DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018009775  a9780226552118  a(DE-B1597)523883  a(OCoLC)1049975071  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHJ70.7b.R83 2018 4aHJ70.7b.R83 2019 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a332/.042091767223  aBE 8620qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/10786:1 aRudnyckyj, Daromir, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond Debt :bIslamic Experiments in Global Finance /cDaromir Rudnyckyj. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b18 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. Pious Finance in the Islamic Global City -- tPart I. Infrastructure -- tPart II. Operations -- tPart III. Problematization -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix A. Methodological Notes -- tAppendix B. Glossary of Islamic Financial Terms -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent economic crises have made the centrality of debt, and the instability it creates, increasingly apparent. This realization has led to cries for change—yet there is little popular awareness of possible alternatives. Beyond Debt describes efforts to create a transnational economy free of debt. Based on ethnographic fieldwork in Malaysia, Daromir Rudnyckyj illustrates how the state, led by the central bank, seeks to make the country’s capital Kuala Lumpur “the New York of the Muslim world”—the central node of global financial activity conducted in accordance with Islam. Rudnyckyj shows how Islamic financial experts have undertaken ambitious experiments to create more stable economies and stronger social solidarities by facilitating risk- and profit-sharing, enhanced entrepreneurial skills, and more collaborative economic action. Building on scholarship that reveals the impact of financial devices on human activity, he illustrates how Islamic finance is deployed to fashion subjects who are at once more pious Muslims and more ambitious entrepreneurs. In so doing, Rudnyckyj shows how experts seek to create a new “geoeconomics”—a global Islamic alternative to the conventional financial network centered on New York, London, and Tokyo. A groundbreaking analysis of a timely subject, Beyond Debt tells the captivating story of efforts to re-center international finance in an emergent Islamic global city and, ultimately, to challenge the very foundations of conventional finance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBonds (Islamic law)zIslamic countries. 0aDebt equity conversionzIslamic countries. 0aFinancexReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aFinance, PubliczIslamic countries. 0aFinance, PubliczMalaysia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aIslam.  aIslamic finance.  aMalaysia.  aalternative finance.  adebt.  adevelopment.  ageoeconomics.  aglobalization.  asocial studies of finance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226552118423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226552118/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles